    {
      "id": "0ad24b6f3b0b7202fee361b0f08206881930eb43",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 109,
        "name": "Christopher J. Morrone",
        "email": "morrone2@llnl.gov",
        "username": "morrone"
      },
      "date": "2014-06-27 21:11:29.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1\n\nI would _highly_ prefer that we not merge together patches when they are packported.  This makes it _significantly_ more difficult for me to compare lists of patches on branches, and discussions in tickets, and see if I have all of the necessary patches really in place.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "62b6cd408ba2fb71c1da3677e336a0e3c3cb492e",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 117,
        "name": "Andreas Dilger",
        "email": "adilger@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "adilger"
      },
      "date": "2014-06-27 23:43:48.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2:\n\nChris, in this case there isn't any value to land the patches separately because the first patch introduces a bug in the code.\n\nI think an acceptable compromise is that the commit message match the two original messages (especially the summary line) so that they can be found in a search. The format for backported patches includes:\n\n Lustre-commit: {git hash on master branch}\n Lustre-change: {Gerrit canonical change URL}\n\nSee Additional Tags section in https://wiki.hpdd.intel.com/display/PUB/Submitting+Changes",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
